                <td height="622" valign="top" colspan="2" bgcolor="#004142">&nbsp;<table width="100%" border="0" cellpadding="4"><tr bgcolor="#000000"><td><font color="#FFFFFF"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial" size="6">Cheating - It&#8217;s Everywhere!</font></td></tr></table><table width="100%" border="0" cellpadding="4" cellspacing="0"><tr><td></td><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif" size="5" COLOR="#FFFFFF">Rating</Font></TD><TD><IMG SRC="images/a4.gif" BORDER=0><A HREF="articleread.php3?article=2471"><IMG SRC="images/aread.GIF" BORDER=0></A><A HREF="articlereview.php3?article=2471"><IMG SRC="images/areview.GIF" BORDER=0></A></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif" size="5" COLOR="#FFFFFF">Author</Font></TD><TD><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2"><A HREF="../membercenter/directory/memberpage.php3?member=6451">Kelly "Gyrotech" Brown</A></FONT></TD></TR><!-- 6451 --><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif" size="5" COLOR="#FFFFFF">Description</Font></TD><TD><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2">It is very easy to cheat in SWCCG. Here are some things to watch for!</FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif" size="5" COLOR="#FFFFFF">Article</Font></TD><TD><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2">Cheating is one of the easiest things to do in a game as flexible as the Star Wars CCG. I mean, they are just cards! They can moved or manipulated in any way. Cheating is a lot harder a game such as Warcraft II unless you actually KNOW how to cheat. Anyway, I have made some keen observations of many player tendencies that literally come off as cheating or &quot;accidentally cheating.&quot;<br>
<br>
The first and most common method I&#146;ve noticed in order to gain more force is when the opponent claims he overpaid for something. Be sure not to let your mind wander when it is not your own turn. Keep count of the force your opponent is using and what they are placing down and do not forget to apply modifiers. One time I was playing against a Ralltir Operations and my opponent paid three force (I carefully watched him pay it) to deploy a non-unique Tempest Scout. I could tell he realized he needed force to move (he had zero left) so he hesitated, looked around, looked down at the card, and said, &quot;Oh, oops, he only costs THREE force.&quot; He then tried to pull back one force when I did a recount for him and he was like, &quot;Oops, my bad.&quot; I cannot describe all of the facial expressions very well but I could tell he had the intent of doing whatever was necessary to get one more force to move his forces away.<br>
<br>
Another common &quot;habit&quot; players do is peek at their destiny before targeting something. It is very common for players to finger their top card so they can easily flip it over when it is time. However, occasionally, I&#146;ll watch them flare a little &quot;too high&quot; and take a glance. Then they come out randomly and say, &quot;Uh, I&#146;m going to target you defense 5 guy&quot; or whatever and they are trying to use a Blaster Rifle or something. Once again, I stopped my opponent and asked him to shuffle his deck (it wasn&#146;t a tournament). He was like, &quot;Why?&quot; I simply responded, &quot;Do you know what the top card is?&quot; &quot;No!&quot; &quot;Then it won&#146;t matter, will it? Shuffle your deck!&quot; Fingering the top card of the Reserve Deck is okay but watch for peekers.<br>
<br>
Another notorious cheat that even I am occasionally guilty of is &quot;accidental overdrawing.&quot; The habit is to draw cards slowly and when you see a card you don&#146;t want (or at least the sign of one), you flick it back down really quickly and say, &quot;Okay, I need to save this much force.&quot; The only right thing to do in this case is make them draw it up.<br>
<br>
Oftentimes, mistakes are made that can be forgiven and just need to be clarified. For example, my friend once tried to Nabrun Leids his assault group into Moff Jerjerrod&#146;s face and smash him when I had Imperial Arrest Order down (which restricts Nabrun and Elis to Move Phase and Exterior Sites). He initiated a battle and we were about to start it when I suddenly remembered my effect. I simply took a couple steps back and let the opponent resume. There is no real punishment or enforcement here.<br>
<br>
Then there is the famous, &quot;I hope he doesn&#146;t count this stack&quot; method. Oftentimes I&#146;ll say something like, &quot;Force drain for 9&quot; and the opponent will just lay this lump onto their lost pile instead of moving the cards one at a time. Being the annoying observer that I am, I always pick that stack up and clarify exactly what cards were lost. Oftentimes people try to make an accurate-LOOKING lump but they don&#146;t really count at all. Always check moved stacks or ask your opponent to move cards one by one.<br>
<br>
There are lots of other cheating methods out there. I barely covered a few. Don&#146;t space when playing a game. Watch the opponent closely and don&#146;t cheat yourself! No being a hypocrite! If you know of any other cheating techniques to watch for, tell me (D-mail or E-mail Gyro@TechEmail.com). </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP" COLSPAN="2"><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2"><a href="articles.php3"><img src="images/aback.GIF" border="0"></a><A HREF="articleread.php3?article=2471"><IMG SRC="images/aread.GIF" BORDER=0></A><A HREF="articlereview.php3?article=2471"><IMG SRC="images/areview.GIF" BORDER=0></A><a href="articleprint.php3?article=2471" TARGET="BLANK_"><img src="images/aprint.gif" border="0"></a></FONT></TD></TR></TABLE> </td>
              </tr>
